The Prague Stock Exchange ended with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions in ČEZ shares reached about half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of commercial Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday's fall when it fell to about 6%.
The drop this time is due to the fall of the shares on Wall Street.
It also expresses the market's reaction to the outcome of the American Assembly of Representatives vote that refused to support the financial sector secretary's stabilization plan.
Fall of actions in Asia
The shares of the Asian Stock Exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although throughout the day the index finally attenuated part of the losses.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index over its financial day marked almost four percent, although it later mitigated its losses by reducing the decline by almost 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index that follows the movements of Chinese shares in the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
The stocks of the Sidney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the Secretary of the Index, fell to 3.6 percent.
"The bailout shares programmed in the U.S. are insecure and this influences the financial market around the world," Hong Kong Bureau Chief Joseph Yam said.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, i.e. without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as those of the United States.
