The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the European Commission's last steps in the area of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
Of this also the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network there is not much chance (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant price decrease to which the classic operators had to react.
At the same time, even before the entrance of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the virtual operator Mobilking's debut in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to get more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group which, apart from this, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, they have fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators usually profile with low costs - offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, often contradicts the offer of the most adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap with respect to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows it can be a good hit also the bet for a trivial nothing target group.
This operator is specifically targeting the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone's spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubted this: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it's about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the financial group Penta, in a telephone conversation for mobil.cz.
Indirectly he assured that the current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it the group GTS Novera who would like to take a step later to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said the group's spokesperson, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they'll spark a better time.
It seems that, by unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said for mobil.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
Other operators refer to the specific nature of the Czech market.
T-mobile's spokesperson, Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
He adds: "In the network of T-Mobile it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied in such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this with regard to the sharing of costs and infrastructure.
Precisely we consider it to be the greatest contribution from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition, which would lead to a fall in prices and thus a fall in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTU was at the time of U:fon's entry by T-Mobile society.
This is witnessed by public information available on ČTU's websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market has not long been open to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephone operator and a virtual operator has been concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for the classical operators," added Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS Department of External Relations, to our question.
These statements are not surprising to the operators' representatives.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Across the country where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the fall in prices does not fall within the interest of UOHS.
Really the dramatic shock in all this case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of petrol in gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position and therefore do not have a corresponding promotion of responsibility in their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," he added to his response Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously a relevant market analysis developed by ČTU, according to which telecommunications is from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market none of the Czech operators naturally has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for UUOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators ascend strikingly in a similar way.
The current complaints from stakeholders (inluded by the above-mentioned GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with the operators they clash with many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in the ČTU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications of which the UOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the extension of ČTU's competition in the field of commercial tendering was introduced recently, although a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be fully known by UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator that already exists in the Czech mobile networks remains unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only some chosen get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be discovered, it would be possible to talk about infringement under the terms of the contract that could be translated into an end to the partnership with the given company," he answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above that they can be made up of thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get a not negligible profit and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they do not in any way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so many percent of customers.
They must also accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators."
This is precisely what should seem to the minimally strange ČTU.
In addition, there is a new question for UOHS.
If mobile operators turn their eyes on this type of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator's entry?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried to protect themselves more or less from this intrusion.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have they defended operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and others began to emerge with it.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority all of this happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really gets to this land, then the Czech mobile phone market is probably starting to move again.
If any of the operators lets a virtual mobile operator in, it will be difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with a male voice and one with a female voice, one with a choir and another with an instrumental voice.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are in charge of the song.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio said before that it intentionally chose for Solo singers with voices representatively young who are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with both of them and then, too, with the Choir to fix themselves in the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would be consistent," he commented.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home played for the first time in 1834 in the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
He gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first stanza of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
