The Prague MHD takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the Prague Transport Company's history describes the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased right now by almost a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card at the transport company's infocentres and posts at the Metro, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka stations.
Bonuses can already be purchased from yesterday on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of commerce can definitely start forgetting about the ticket sales posts at the subway stations, where so far they had to queue regularly to get a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is charged to one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is at the passenger's disposal a window with prepared staff that helps interested people with the purchase over the internet and also with the recharge of the bonus purchased on their card," said the project spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to reload the electronic bonus on the Opencard in the vending machines that are located in some subway halls.
How are these vending machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket-picking machine and the travelers will probably have already noticed them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are in the city five but by the end of the year there would have to be eighty", Opatrný added.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter in it the Opencard chip card and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
The electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, on the bypass trains and bus lines from the number 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of the localities of Central Bohemia.
"In the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reading card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the bond area," explained the check of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that establishes the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
Circumvalation buses have their reading cards mounted in the driver's locker.
Upon entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also it is necessary to accompany it with the Opencard in the place intended for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel on bypass buses and do not remember when they are finished the validity of the bonus can go to the vending machines where the cards are charged.
Here, on the screen of the machine, you will be shown the information about the validity of your document.
