'May Blood', Garci's epic bet
Inspired by the National Episodes of Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Garci recreates the famous uprising of the Spanish against the French in May Blood, which is the most ambitious film in his filmography with about 15 million euros of budget.
In this way, the filmmaker has tried to "illustrate the torrent of characters and social analysis" that he has always admired in the work of the well-known novelist, he has explained today during the presentation of the tape, with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of a wide cast of interpreters.
Blood of May, with a film more than two and a half hours, is premiered this Friday in the cinemas, to become in the future a miniseries for Telemadrid of more than four hours duration.
A great admirer of Galdós' literature, José Luis Garci claims to have fulfilled this film "a dream of childhood", which must thank Esperanza Aguirre, who from the Community of Madrid commissioned him three years ago to shoot a commemorative tape for the second centenary of May 2, Madrid, something that he accepted as long as the story was based on the National Episodes.
The 15 million budget that the Community of Madrid has contributed in its entirety constitutes for Garci a "unique opportunity" to set up with the decorated and the appropriate clothing the portrait of "an atolondrada Spain that was wrong to fight for, since, the struggle for independence led the people to enormous delay with the reign of Fernando VII", he pointed out.
But the filmmaker regrets not having counted on a funding like that of Alatriste or The Ghosts of Goya - more than twice as much as that of Blood of May-, so he has not been able to shoot some scenes framed in a script signed with Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he has collaborated in almost his entire career.
For this reason, the director of Back to Start, has influenced in which is his usual form of work, the staging with the actors, with whom he usually rehearses before starting the shooting and to whom he does not cast, because it seems "humiliating" and consider that "part of the director's job lies in going to the theater and the cinema to know what happens in the industry in which he works".
Many of the interpreters who match in May's Blood repeat before his camera, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Candidate for the Oscar on four occasions - of which he won one-, Garci considers that any of the three candidates to represent Spain this year before the Hollywood Academy, the Blood of May itself, Seven French Billiard Tables and the finally selected, The Blind Sunflowers, do not represent a young generation of Spanish cinema, "which is the one to be made known", he said.
With this movie Garci does not expect prizes.
"In the beginning you think you work for posterity, then you realize that you only work for prosperity, and now you settle for making one more movie," explains Garci after more than 30 years of professional career.
Isabel Bayón recovers the essence of the Seville dancer Tortola Valencia
A Seville dancer is going to pay tribute to a Seville dancer too.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia, of Catalan father (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old moved to London with her family.
She was a free dance dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, pioneer of women's liberation, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian and advocated the abolition of the corset that prevented free women's movement.
The life of this woman who marked a dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe between wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me and I thought it was amazing."
According to the dancer, "we do not intend to count his life but to gather his spirit.
The titles of his dances have suggested flamenco sticks.
So, "the butterfly dance" suggested a guajira, or "the snake dance" some tangos.
Her dance was sexy and I was told that my dance is also within this aesthetic," she says.
The assembly has two exceptional collaborations: that of Miguel Poveda who will sing again to Isabel in one of his shows, as he did in the one of "The Open Door"; and with the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to collaborate with whoever his student was.
"Matilde makes Tortola the oldest, the character of maturity.
I am happy that I have accepted to act in my work and I am very honored by it."
The assembly also features the musical composition and guitars of Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, the song of Miguel Ortega, El Pulga and Moi de Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the violin of Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfra Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal companion of this type of artists who were divas in all its extension, and who are always in love with them".
The work also tells in some way the life of this woman who developed in places as far away, especially for the time, such as India, the United States, or Russia, as well as throughout Europe, as she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to remind her because I think she is one of those women who have a huge influence at a given time and now no one knows and much less values her work," says Bayón.
The show will start today at 8.30 p.m. at the Lope de Vega Theatre.
