I'm sure more than one has been told he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (sleep pee) or sleepwalking, but it doesn't have to be so.
As mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcited situations.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or otherwise (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense the child should be observed and consulted with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him/her a way out.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, except that it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress disorder).
What can be done is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some internal calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter dream.
Once the sleepyos appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and is therefore resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes you should consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common thing), do not fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because being asleep isn't conscious enough to organize his thinking.
Besides, you will hear what he says, but you don't know what he's dreaming to say that, so be very careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
