The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, he regained the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not happen again.
While Judge Krever was late in presenting his relationship, some provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of the people still trusted the blood system in Quebec," Décary recalls.
The situation was disappointing.
After having made a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing the birth in Europe of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of those who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago, it has been shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: tests of nucleid acid that allow the presence of the virus in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleid acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We therefore substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500,000 blood products each year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product.
I think you can today receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover your health without worry," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
"We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary says before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which groups on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All healthy, 18-year-olds who meet the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travelled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since life today is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate his blood, " says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We celebrated a few weeks ago, the laying on the bench of our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these a year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year, " says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood intake program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this, " as Hema-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
