If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of persecutions for defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to examine the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by cluttering.
It was sufficient for the mining company to open its books, files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and support letters for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can call for a "public " debate by disregarding his views?
According to the vice president, it seems that this word only designates highly paid lawyers and not for all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or what you don't want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does it especially because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes in arguments, and not on what many people perceive as a persecution-breeding (persecuting " public debate " , Barrick Gold has just filed a requirement with respect to the authors of Noir Canada intimidating them to no longer use this word).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and truth, essential for all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the wealthy companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold truly wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so in accordance with the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he claims, he does not want to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices to limit this kind of abusive persecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
It envisages in particular: better control by the elected representatives of their implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized the lack of payment, as well as a right of control over the wages paid to the leaders of the aided companies.
The American Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day round of negotiations.
" We are making great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets, " said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
" Everything has been done to cover the economy and the ordinary Americans in the face of the current Wall Street crisis, " explained the Democrat.
" It's the fundamental point: if we don't do this, trauma, chaos, and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense, " said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had been over very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect of a further failure on investors' mood.
The last hour that had been set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who had joined the negotiations late, were rather in favour of the agreement, without forgetting to express their discontent with being forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain arrangements to reach the agreement, particularly that which would allow the owners to keep their home and that on the salary of the leaders of the surviving companies by the state.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, no congratulations are due.
But these measures are necessary, " he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, interrogated in another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that: " I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it. "
" The important points I have read [show] that it is something we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said that the option of doing nothing is not acceptable. "
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the doubtful debts, the risky and unsellable assets of the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the explosion of a real estate bubble that first led to the sinking of mortgage risk credits before it spreads to other more common forms of debt securities (PCAAs) and triggers a liquidity freeze and an outpouring of banks and financial institutions.
It's a group of Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe that we have come out of the deadlock since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to smooth the roughness for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision stipulating that if the government had to take losses for five years with this program, it could impose new fees that would try to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which 100 more billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote from Congress.
In exchange for your help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will be worth dividends in case of profits and that it will be able to resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the embargo procedures for housing obtained from real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on remuneration and cash compensation paid to the leaders of the companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote of the House of Representatives from today and that of the Senate next Wednesday.
