What were they producing at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Very soon, on 8 October, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing frauds of significant harm, in a business-like manner, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Office of the Prosecutor, the funds obtained in public competitions were used for their own purposes, often justifying the performance of tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the municipalities - in total about 65 million HUF - stopped in part in the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal and in part in the pocket of private people.
The method, which was also made known by the researchers, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the various associations never fulfilled their obligations assumed.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were fake.
For this purpose they obtained the heelwork in the market of the District of Józsefváros and the circular seals were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that on behalf of which company the counterfeit invoice was to be made was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent to Istvan Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and these were used as a model to make the invoices they presented, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, the Ministry of Social and Labour Affairs, as well as in the City Council of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András, who, according to our information, wrote the necessary reports to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Sides chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic centre provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the center manager - so many people do not fit at the same time in that place.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
For a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, yet on the bill there were one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of the great fantasy invoice also exaggerated when they pointed to the gastronomic center Pigal Kft. because in the holding of books of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of that company, informed hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecution and he was shown the invoices, he knew that they were false documents.
"On the stamp the name of our company and the NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal problems he also did not agree that according to the bill, 100 people were accommodated, since they have only eleven rooms in which not so many people fit.
In addition, meals were also included on the bill, while the restaurant has not been working for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice makers were also not informed that the travel agency elected in Budapest exclusively organizes trips abroad, so that in the cash payment invoice they foolishly indicated as a service a journey within Hungary, which did not coincide with the practice of issuing invoices from the agency.
Furthermore, as was known during the investigation, VAT was also included in the document, despite the fact that travel outside the territory of the European Union was tax-free.
Among other things the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Revfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért foundation, since the services of that company are not loaded with a 25 but only 15 percent VAT, besides the hotel employees only extended invoices made by machine however the invoice was manual.
In addition, the "shippers" made other mistakes as well, as in the case of a company in which they put on the invoice as an activity carried out the road transport to which - it was learned during the investigations of the prosecution - does not carry out the company founded as investment consultant.
Also due to formal differences - inadequate format of the invoice, false seal - it was known that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont are false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives refused to issue such invoices.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that when the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation process, that is why the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - refused to issue such a document.
They consciously cleared the invoices.
Another group of manufacturers of fake invoices are those who were aware that they had to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about HUF 4 million on behalf of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
According to the prosecution, one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, convinced the manager of the Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
Similarly, the Biogate Kft., currently under liquidation, collaborated with Zuschlag and his accomplices, which in 2003 provided invoices worth approximately HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület Association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület Association, with no real economic activity behind.
There was no movement of capital either, as they then cancelled the prepared invoices but forgot to include this entity in their documents.
The next group of fake invoice manufacturers include those who have some connection with the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the defendant of the Ukrainian manager of the Budapest-based Delta Trio SL, who dealt with fuel and vehicle trade.
This company issued numerous invoices worth approximately HUF 18 million in the months of October, November and December 2005 on the sale of computers.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by the Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also dispatched documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov recognized during the investigation that issued invoices on behalf of the company for Atlasz, for Hoppa and for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány charging the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies actually worked because - according to the defendant - they did not receive work.
But he took advantage of these companies, as at the request of his accomplice lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company's registration documents, sent invoices on behalf of the companies for the organizations associated with Zuschlag: for Atlasz and for Y-Generáció.
Kubatov on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade gave a total of 15 invoices to different entities worth HUF 14.2 million.
The Office of the Prosecutor considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the invoice amount.
This man even took advantage of the company in command Szi-Beri to issue fictitious invoices used in the Biztos Pont competition.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség to Modern Magyarországért presented a contest in January 2006 to Tancsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
From the contest they obtained 500 thousand HUF respectively, but did not use the money for the objectives of the contest.
For this not to be discovered, they submitted to the TMA five fictitious invoices received from the Works Team Kft.
These were the invoices found during the registration of the office that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the defendants will probably report in the trial - as they did in the Prosecutor's Office - the course of forgery of the invoices.
