The question is: what interest do you have to do it?, because perhaps in exchange for the return of most of the money - fifty million HUF - the socialists reached an agreement with him so that Zussi would assume all the responsibilities.
Who, on the other hand, for these days could even be offended, since to alleviate his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied him.
While the numerous perpetrators of economic crimes of much higher value, who never returned the money, walked freely or at least could wait in their own home for the sentence, he has no chance for that.
Psychology of Overlays: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the economics of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played the lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime, the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI).
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, the loss of the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-prize" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention in order not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was promised that if they won, they would receive 15 dollars more prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group playing "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
So far, they explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
Around five hundred million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; they are characteristic of the infection of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses dependent on the pathogen are spread through two main forms: Hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), Hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
It is recommended that travellers should be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, and no vaccines are available against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifest by means of poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this, jaundice appears in the skin and in the white of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die in the world of cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that, according to the calculations, only one in ten infected patients receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control, is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently some 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus of the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30th is the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less who believes in God?
According to a recent research, religious faith has a soothing effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University carried out an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the context of this singular experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shock, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis occurred as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, work of Sassoferrato of the 17th century and the Lady of the arm of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that period while observing the religious theme painting or the other.
The Catholics affirmed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "were reassured and peace reigned in their hearts".
When they watched the religious picture they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can get a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really changes our personality" - Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if Madonna de Leonardo or another painter of her own size were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary produce even better results?
