(At the same time, the federal government managed to secure on the pretext of strengthening the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand web addresses and a few thousand search phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of websites and keywords of the last two months.)
This is quite contradictory the opinion about Google: it is criticized by those who fear to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their privacy is impaired when they start using Google's services, and they rebel against it as against multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the North American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users of other countries, see in them the future generation, the "coupling of the vanguard", not so much to their rival, Microsoft, catalogued by their Windows as conqueror of the World, however much they both struggle for the same goal.
This can happen because Google unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the program package free, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it can also be because geeks see with precision the very problematic relationship between people's rights and the Internet that occurred precisely because of one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the available communication channels, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Shanghai, and can even join them with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, after which they can be included in a tracking system such as the FriendFeed or the Blip.fm, can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored in the Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
We can know many cases from which it turns out that, for example, the bride, seeing the flow of photographs the next morning of the common friends, finds out who she spent the night with her fraudulent boyfriend or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the management of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person's "on line" life is what she shows of herself - this is the definition that hides behind the behavior of the youth of our day.
And whoever wants to hide something, or at least wants to dodge Google's monopoly, can do it (starting with the Scroogle that uses Google's search system, but leaves no trace).
There are many people who don't want to register on the collective pages to prevent them from being found, but Google's "on-line" apps can be replaced, from text writing software to image and news reading applications with alternative versions that don't connect to giant servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion almost openly expects the day Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of 156 billion dollars is worth more than the IBM (140 billion dollars), the Intel (124 billion dollars) or the Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while the services that are introduced more and more quickly cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also to numerous other software developers.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, the senior management strongly rejected the employee's protest after doubling the company's child care price, considered too expensive the unlimited number of employees' feeding, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to pressure from the Chinese government and the company according to the agreement filtered all information that violated the good morals and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal regulations says that they will not announce any new services in advance, but only when it is ready to work, which if it is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to revolutionize the world: while some believe that Google's scanning and archiving of books and magazines will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the U.S. Supreme Court, others fear its health system, because in it we can create our own complete health profile, with previous analysis, with our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for writers of science fiction works, the Scroogled, novel of the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwelian form that future, in which a man only of the data of Google can be described alarmingly well.
