The smart car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not imitation of the sensors of obstacles existing in nature?
For example, that of the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CETEC in Japan, the bumblebees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C-type robotic driving system imitating nature, to which they gave the characteristics of the bumblebees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
The eyes composed of the bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of composite eyes, the engineers used the laser length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the project of the robot of vehicles.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety cap, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bumblebee does to avoid other bumblebees.
This process must be carried out in one opening and closing the eyes.
However, unlike the bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the turning direction of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the bumblebees to avoid other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotary movement and the acceleration in addition to the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and are higher in energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, much less the storage capacity.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No memories of gigabytes, no megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into the series models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles in his path.
