Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and fell by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Industrial selling prices rose only to a minimal extent, with 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors rose marginally, by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The largest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to the 4.6 per cent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper manufacturing, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry, prices rose between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight in domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, which was of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally they increased prices by 10.2 percent.
Electricity prices, gas, heat and water supplies exceeded the previous year's prices by 18.7 per cent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, in the energy and intermediate sector prices there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, as compared to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods producing branches, there was a 6.8 per cent decrease and in investment goods 1.4 per cent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a 3.9 per cent decrease.
The price of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro and by 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
