Járóka: Breaking the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host is France, which this year is also President-in-Office of the European Union.
Livia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations against Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for employment, social affairs and equal opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press bureau of the Fidesz group of deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Gypsies stay out of the labour market in the first place because of their low level of schooling.
"Most young Gypsies have not finished middle school and because of the poor quality of basic education, only a small part of them can obtain a university degree."
Járóka further stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, plays a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in early education for Roma children can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise these issues widely among both Roma and non-Gypsies.
The sooner a gypsy student starts school, the more opportunities they will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and to ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - highlighted Livia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary in order to accelerate immediately the processes of school disintegration, for which it is of fundamental importance the correct compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights", Járóka demanded.
The objective of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting held in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
