Goodbye to the old cinema Paradise, the cities cancel the historic halls
Historical cinemas close favoring the Multiplexes.
"A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the major Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, which with the birth of the great methicons on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear almost always are historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize in Cannes, which counted the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that maybe lost forever.
The figures given by Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and most of them are paid for in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are as first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas less, following Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for its disappearance is the multiplex, these three Italian regions are their own that have recorded the largest number of new methicone cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to methicones.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interestingly the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned by the closures, decided to repair itself with the signature of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono room is in the historical center that on the periphery.
Among the rules provided for there are means of tax facilitation for managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special parking fees.
"It's an initiative I like," notes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, that in order to contrast the extra power of methicones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that was always important to me: the closure of Bagheria's cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Paradise cinema", which I already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass through the Rialto or the Quirinale of via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, in order not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side».
